Notebook 1 - Setting Up a Place to Start¶

Introduction¶

This notebook is the experimentation of a starting point. Source is inspired by https://github.com/llSourcell/How-to-Generate-Art-Demo/blob/master/demo.ipynb. The findings in this notebook will be taken into account when working on any future notebooks. For the most part, this notebook will be formatted in a way that will show the progress of experiementation. The main layout style will be by date then a title for the section.

Here's the citation for original paper where the VGG16 network is described in detail:

Very Deep Convolutional Networks for Large-Scale Image Recognition, K. Simonyan, A. Zisserman, arXiv:1409.1556

Pre-dating July 12th, 2017 - Initial Research¶

Before July 12th, 2017, quiet a bit of research was put into how to go about the presentation of the project. I found Jupyter to be the answer after trying to install the required python packages for using Keras with a Tensorflow backend. Anaconda and Jupyter notebook seemed to jump right out as it provided a simple setup. I still had a little difficulty at first but it was better than having to complie packages like 'scipy' just for use on Windows. A final decision on the use of Anaconda and Jupyter were made final and put into action.

Aside¶

WinPython was looked into and it was ultimately decided that it did not solve the installation issues that I had previously faced when just using python on it's own.

Aside - July 13th, 2017¶

I had trouble at first figuring out what was wrong with the images I chose as the array dimensions were not matching which meant I could not perform transformations on them. As if turned out I was trying to use an RGBA image format, which meant an extra depth to one of the dimensions. I added a way to mitigate the issue, now JPG and PNG files should work.

def content_loss(content, combination):
    return backend.sum(backend.square(combination - content))

layer_features = layers['block2_conv2']
content_image_features = layer_features[0, :, :, :]
combination_features = layer_features[2, :, :, :]

loss += content_weight * content_loss(content_image_features,
                                      combination_features)
In [13]:
def gram_matrix(x):
    features = backend.batch_flatten(backend.permute_dimensions(x, (2, 0, 1)))
    gram = backend.dot(features, backend.transpose(features))
    return gram
In [14]:
def style_loss(style, combination):
    S = gram_matrix(style)
    C = gram_matrix(combination)
    channels = 3
    size = height * width
    return backend.sum(backend.square(S - C)) / (4. * (channels ** 2) * (size ** 2))

feature_layers = ['block1_conv2', 'block2_conv2',
                  'block3_conv3', 'block4_conv3',
                  'block5_conv3']
for layer_name in feature_layers:
    layer_features = layers[layer_name]
    style_features = layer_features[1, :, :, :]
    combination_features = layer_features[2, :, :, :]
    sl = style_loss(style_features, combination_features)
    loss += (style_weight / len(feature_layers)) * sl
In [15]:
def total_variation_loss(x):
    a = backend.square(x[:, :height-1, :width-1, :] - x[:, 1:, :width-1, :])
    b = backend.square(x[:, :height-1, :width-1, :] - x[:, :height-1, 1:, :])
    return backend.sum(backend.pow(a + b, 1.25))

loss += total_variation_weight * total_variation_loss(combination_image)
In [16]:
grads = backend.gradients(loss, combination_image)
In [17]:
outputs = [loss]
outputs += grads
f_outputs = backend.function([combination_image], outputs)

def eval_loss_and_grads(x):
    x = x.reshape((1, height, width, 3))
    outs = f_outputs([x])
    loss_value = outs[0]
    grad_values = outs[1].flatten().astype('float64')
    return loss_value, grad_values

class Evaluator(object):

    def __init__(self):
        self.loss_value = None
        self.grads_values = None

    def loss(self, x):
        assert self.loss_value is None
        loss_value, grad_values = eval_loss_and_grads(x)
        self.loss_value = loss_value
        self.grad_values = grad_values
        return self.loss_value

    def grads(self, x):
        assert self.loss_value is not None
        grad_values = np.copy(self.grad_values)
        self.loss_value = None
        self.grad_values = None
        return grad_values

evaluator = Evaluator()
In [18]:
x = np.random.uniform(0, 255, (1, height, width, 3)) - 128.

iterations = 10

for i in range(iterations):
    print('Start of iteration', i)
    start_time = time.time()
    x, min_val, info = fmin_l_bfgs_b(evaluator.loss, x.flatten(),
                                     fprime=evaluator.grads, maxfun=20)
    print('Current loss value:', min_val)
    end_time = time.time()
    print('Iteration %d completed in %ds' % (i, end_time - start_time))

July 13th, 2017 - Notebook Review¶

In the output image there is colour comming through, I did not think of this but I should convert the input image to the a percieved greyscale version of itself so that the output is a pure greyscale image. This goes with the style reference image also, perhaps a more realistic drawing would be of a better choice. The results in the output image are still pretty good, simply changing the input images could help improve the output better. As of right now, using my cpu power, the whole program takes just above 2 hours t o complete. This is not desirable. VGG16 is trained on alot of images and is a fairly large neural network. Reducing the size of the network should reduce caluclations and provide a better runtime and is a more preferable option to just adding more computing power (using GPU instead of CPU).

I have images that I will scan to experiment with.
